passages.text: Equity ResearchAugust 28,2025

DOCU is down 16% YTD vs IGV up 9% as investors fear that AI will disrupt SW apps + questions linger on the health of the bus. after 1Q's billings miss. For 2Q,we believe 5% billings growth ests. are reasonable + note easy comps. DOCU trades at a 17% discount to peers on '26 FCF. Given persistent AI displacement fears, we believe valuation may stay under pressure unless 2Q billings top the hist. beat avg. of 4% + investors see enough proof of IAM monetization.

**Easy Setup in 2Q.** Billings and total rev will face the easiest comps of the year in F2Q before facing the second-toughest comps of the year in F3Q. Following last Q's billings miss and subsequent FY26 billings downgrade, we believe ests. calling for 5% billings growth are appropriate. Ests. for 6% total revenue growth and 27% non-GAAP op. margin also seem reasonable.

1. **Billings Dynamic.** Recall that last Q, billings came in 1 pt short of the guide due to GTM changes that disincentivized early renewal deals that weren't expansion deals. Mgmt. attributed the miss to timing rather than demand, as they had expected this dynamic to occur later in FY26 and usage remained stable in May. We note that GTM issues are usually resolved over time,and we will look for commentary around further disruption to billings.

2. **IAM Traction + GTM Updates.** Our checks indicate that competition is heating up with Conga and that IAM's functionality is still early, especially within the enterprise. IAM's GTM is also still early, especially for the enterprise: Mgmt. has been indicating for the last few Qs that they will focus on IAM expansion for small to mid-size customers while continuing to roll out to enterprises on a department-level basis.

3. **Margin Leverage Update.** Recall that the FY26 margin guide was maintained last Q at 28.3% at the midpoint vs. 29.8% in FY25. Given that peers are in the high 30s and 85% of deals are touched by a human, we highlight DOCU's margin opportunity with self-service, which saw impressive momentum last Q and drove ~1k new IAM customers despite being launched only in April without any marketing campaigns.

Alternative Data Indicators Positive for 2Q. We analyzed alternative data from Similarweb and Sensor Tower to understand demand trends among individuals and SMB customers (85% of customer base but 15% of rev). For 2Q, web traffic grew 12% y/y (vs. 5% in 1Q), and monthly average users to DOCU's mobile app grew 2% y/y (vs. 1% decline in 1Q). We believe the uptick could be due to the launch of self- service for IAM in April, but we note that DOCU is early in its self- service journey for the overall platform. See inside for more.

Our Thoughts on the Stock. Valuation remains attractive at 15x '26 FCF vs. peers at 18x (17% discount). While we view fundamentals as intact, we think the multiple will continue to be impaired by AI disruption fears in the short term until investors see sufficient proof of IAM monetization. Maintain Buy.
Chart 2 - DOCU Non-GAAP Operating Margins Improving But Still Lags Peers
Source: Jefferies Research, Company Data; Note: Peer Group includes ADBE, CRM, BOX, and DBX.

We are appreciative of DocuSign's e- signature technology and the growth opportunity ahead, especially given the large number of penetrated TAM. Long- term catalysts include international expansions increased agreement cloud adoption, and the up- sell/cross- sell opportunity. The new mgmt team is changing the playbook - driving GTM efficiency with more reliance on self- service model and reinvesting savings in product with focus on creating one unified architecture for acqs. and core. We believe the stock trades attractively at current levels.
Risk/Reward - 12 Month View

- Revenue CAGR of 8% from F23 to F26E, driven by an under-penetrated TAM, international traction, and some Agreement Cloud adoption.- Operating margin leverage of 8% in F23-F26E, driven by leverage in sales and marketing.- DCF-based price target of \(\) 105\(implies 6.9x FY26E revenue.\)

- Revenue CAGR of more than 12% from F23-F26E, driven by an underpenetrated TAM, higher international traction, and increased Agreement Cloud adoption.- Operating margin leverage of 12%+ from F23-F26E driven by leverage in sales and marketing.- DCF-based price target of \(\) 141\(implies 9.3x FY26E revenue.\)

- Revenue CAGR of less than 4% from F23-F26E, driven by lack of execution.- Operating margin leverage less than 3% from F23-F26E, driven by leverage in sales and marketing.- DCF-based price target of \(\) 60\(implies 3.8x FY26E revenue.\)

Top Material Issue(s): 1) Data Security: DOCU stores customer contracts that contain private and sensitive information, so the security of users' data is one of its highest priorities. 2) Systemic Risk Mgmt: DOCU serves its customers from third-party data center hosting facilities and cloud computing platform providers. Any disruption or damage to, or failure of its systems generally, including the systems of its third-party platform providers could result in operations to its services.
Company Target(s): 1) Committed to reaching net-zero no later than 2050. 2) Targeting 100% renewable energy across operations and data centers.

Qs to Mgmt: 1) What actions are management taking to reach its 100% renewable energy targets across operations and data centers? 2) What is management investing in to protect the firm and customers' data? 3) What measures is management taking to ensure that its customer's data is secure when hosted in a third-party data center hosting facility?
- International expansion.- Successful up-/cross-sell within the current customer base.- Higher margins driven by additional cost-cutting measures.- Earnings.

Given the consumer-facing nature of much of DOCU's business, we analyzed alternative data from Similarweb and Sensor Tower to get an indication of recent demand. We note that while 84% of total customers in fiscal 2025 were digital (individuals or SMBs), this customer cohort contributed only 15% of revenues; the other 85% of revenues were generated by enterprise & commercial customers, which might be harder to track via alternative data.

**Our analysis of alternative data was positive, as monthly website visits and daily active users both** **accelerated y/y. Although we view management's investments in self-service and PLG positively,** **we believe it may take time before the benefits are realized.**

Looking at DocuSign website traffic from Similarweb, we found that traffic grew 12% year-over-year in 2Q, above 5% in 1Q on an easier compare. On an absolute basis, website visits were 308k in 2Q,above 290k in 1Q (seasonal).
Chart 4 - DOCU Monthly Website Visits
Source: Jefferies, SimilarWeb.

Monthly average users to DocuSign's mobile app grew 2% on a year-over-year basis, better than a 1% decline in 1Q on an easier compare. On an absolute basis, our alternative data analysis tracked 17.2M users in DocuSign's mobile app in 2Q, below 19.3M in 1Q. We note that mobile app visits remain above pre-pandemic levels of 3- 6M and early pandemic levels of 14- 16M.
Chart 5 - DOCU Quarterly Average Mobile Users
Source:Jefferies, Sensor Tower

DocuSign provides cloud- based electronic signature solutions as well as adjacent functionality around authentication, collaboration, data collection, workflow automation and storage.
Our \(\) 105\(PT is derived via DCF analysis. Key downside risks include increase in churn due to macro pressures and an increase in competition.

Our \(\) 590\(price target is based on 20x EV/EBITDA (slightly below the historical average), applied to our estimates in 5 - 8 quarters. Risks include execution at scale, competitive marketing in the tech market, M&A integration, subs not being immune to recessions, and threat from generative AI solutions.

Our \(\) 30\(PT is derived via DCF. Key risks include fragmented market competition, including deep - pocketed incumbents; the ability to maintain R&D execution to expand into adjacent markets; and non - voting share class risk.
Our Price Target of \(\) 675\$ is based on a DCF. Key risks include the PC cycle and risks related to revenues and margins as MSFT transitions to the Cloud.
Our \(\) 375\$ price target is based on a DCF (CoE 11%; TGR 5%) analysis. Key risks include significant deceleration in New Subscription ACV and margin compression.
